## Common Myths That Create Problems

### Myth 1: "All Mountain Roads Are the Same"
Mountain highways vary dramatically in construction, maintenance, and safety standards. Highway 82 over Independence Pass includes numerous switchbacks and narrow sections without guardrails. I-70 through Glenwood Canyon features modern engineering with wider lanes and safety barriers.

Elevation changes affect different routes uniquely. Independence Pass gains over 4,000 feet in elevation from Aspen, creating significant altitude stress on vehicles and passengers. The Glenwood Springs route maintains more consistent elevation, reducing mechanical stress and passenger discomfort.

Emergency services availability differs substantially between routes. I-70 corridor maintains regular patrol presence and roadside assistance. Remote passes like Independence Pass may have limited cell coverage and extended emergency response times.

### Myth 2: "Four-Wheel Drive Solves Everything"
Four-wheel drive improves traction but doesn't address other mountain driving challenges. Braking distance increases on steep descents regardless of drive system. Altitude affects engine performance and fuel efficiency equally across all drive configurations.

All-wheel drive vehicles handle better in snow conditions but require appropriate tires for optimal performance. Many rental vehicles include all-season tires unsuitable for mountain winter conditions. Professional services maintain appropriate tire selection for seasonal conditions.

Ground clearance becomes more important than drive configuration on certain routes. Scraped undercarriages occur frequently on Independence Pass due to steep approach angles, affecting all vehicle types regardless of drive system.

### Myth 3: "GPS Always Finds the Best Route"
GPS systems often default to shortest distance rather than optimal travel time. During winter months, GPS may suggest closed passes or dangerous routes unsuitable for current conditions. Local knowledge surpasses automated routing for mountain travel.

Real-time traffic data doesn't account for seasonal road closures or construction delays. GPS updates lag behind actual conditions, particularly in remote mountain areas with limited connectivity.

Elevation changes aren't weighted appropriately in most GPS calculations. A route showing 30 minutes shorter travel time might require climbing over 12,000-foot passes, actually extending journey time significantly during adverse conditions.

